ce:section.ce:para:
To further rule out the effect of graphite nitrogen content and determine the elemental composition and valence of the carbon dots, X­ray photoelectron spectroscopy (XPS) was performed. As shown in Fig. 3F, the full XPS spectra display that the surfaces of R-CQDs, Y-CQDs, G-CQDs, and B-CQDs contain three typical peaks of C 1 s (285 eV), N 1 s (399 eV), and O 1 s (532 eV), indicating that they all contain C, N, and O elements. From B-CQDs to R-CQDs, their oxygen/carbon atom ratio decreased from 25.7 % to 13.2 %, while the nitrogen content increased from 8.34 % to 13.74 % and the nitrogen/carbon atom ratio increased from 11.44 % to 18.04 % (Table 1
                        ), indicating an increase in nitrogen-containing functional groups from B-CQDs to R-CQDs. In the high-resolution XPS spectra (Fig. 3G and Fig. 4
                        ), the C 1 s spectra can be deconvoluted into CC/CC (284.5 eV), CN (285.5 eV), CO (286.3 eV) and COOH (288.8 eV). The N 1 s spectra can be deconvoluted into pyridine nitrogen (398.9 eV), pyrrole nitrogen (399.5 eV) and graphite nitrogen (400.6 eV). The O 1 s spectrum can be deconvoluted into CO (532.2 eV) and CO (533.3 eV).[14,17,27] The sp2 carbon content (CC/CC) increased from 0.39 to 0.49 from B-CQDs to R-CQDs, and the graphitic nitrogen content hardly changed (from 0.23 to 0.24) (Table 2
                        ). This indicates that the size of the sp2 conjugated structural domains in these carbon dots increased slightly after solvothermal reaction, which is consistent with the TEM results and verifies that the graphitic nitrogen content is not responsible for controlling multicolor luminescence of carbon dots.
